         <h1>I. Bernard Cohen, 89, Dies; Pioneer in History of Science </h1>
           <div class="row">
               <div class="col-md-10">
 					<p class="text-left">
<blue>1</blue>I. Bernard Cohen , a Newton scholar and Harvard educator whose life 's work molded the history of physical science as an academic discipline in the United States , died on June 20 at his home in Waltham , Mass . <br><blue>2</blue>He was 89 . <br><blue>3</blue>Dr. Cohen joined the Harvard faculty as an instructor in physics in 1942 and retired in 1984 as the Victor S. Thomas professor emeritus of the history of science . <br><blue>4</blue>He taught adult classes in the Harvard Extension School and undergraduate seminars until three years ago and never ceased publishing ; his latest book , relating the story of numbers , is on the way to the printer . <br><blue>5</blue>His interests in the history of science ranged widely , though he was best known for his study of the work of Isaac Newton . <br><blue>6</blue>He published about 20 books , starting in 1941 and including classics that remain in print and on college library shelves , and more than 150 articles , including an interview with Albert Einstein just before his death . <br><blue>7</blue>In 1957 , Dr. Cohen joined the quest to produce a comprehensive edition of Newton 's most important work , the '' Principia Mathematica , '' that included not only its first three editions but also Newton 's original manuscript from 1687 and the voluminous annotations and corrections that Newton made in his personal copies . <br><blue>8</blue>That 900-page volume was published in 1972 , a year after Dr. Cohen heralded it with his '' Introduction to Newton 's ' Principia ' '' ( Harvard University Press , 1971 ) . <br><blue>9</blue>In it , he traced the genesis of Newton 's masterwork and its later editions . <br><blue>10</blue>Dr. Cohen then collaborated with Anne Miller Whitman , a Harvard-trained Latinist , to translate from Latin into English what actually had been the third , 1726 edition of Newton 's original . <br><blue>11</blue>It was published in 1999 by the University of California Press . <br><blue>12</blue>Dr. Cohen made his debut as an author with '' Benjamin Franklin 's Experiments '' ( Harvard , 1941 ) , which was the first scholarly , annotated edition of Franklin 's writings on electricity . <br><blue>13</blue>His doctoral adviser at Harvard decided that it should be his Ph.D. dissertation in 1947 , rather than his intended dissertation . <br><blue>14</blue>His intended dissertation instead became another book , '' Franklin and Newton : An Inquiry into Speculative Newtonian Experimental Science and Franklin 's Work in Electricity as an Example Thereof '' ( 1956 ; revised edition , Harvard , 1973 ) . <br><blue>15</blue>Dr. Cohen eventually combined nine of his previously published Franklin papers , with some addenda , in '' Benjamin Franklin 's Science '' ( 1990 , Harvard ) . <br><blue>16</blue>Bernard Cohen was born in the Far Rockaway section of New York City . <br><blue>17</blue>He graduated from Columbia Grammar School and entered Harvard as a freshman in 1933 after sampling New York University , a veterinary medical college in Farmingdale , N.Y. , and the Valley Forge Military Academy in Wayne , Pa . <br><blue>18</blue>He received his bachelor of science degree and a Phi Beta Kappa key at Harvard in 1937 after concentrating on mathematics . <br><blue>19</blue>He was among the first to enroll in Harvard 's new Program in the History of Science and Learning when Dr. James B. Conant started it and the first , in 1947 , to receive a Ph.D. in the history of science . <br><blue>20</blue>During World War II he taught physics and mathematics to Navy personnel sent to the campus for crash courses . <br><hr><br><blue>1(10)</blue>: <m_str>Newton 's</m_str> (9_9) 	<m_str>Newton 's</m_str> (7_15) 	<m_str>its</m_str> (9_13) 	<m_str>Newton 's</m_str> (10_30) 	<m_str>Newton</m_str> (7_50) 	<m_str>Newton</m_str> (14_12) 	<m_str>Newton 's</m_str> (7_37) 	<m_str>his</m_str> (7_53) 	<m_str>Isaac Newton</m_str> (5_23) 	<m_str>Newton 's</m_str> (8_21) 	<br><blue>2(2)</blue>: <m_